      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "An evil, an only evil,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc. The words imply that the evil would be unique in character, attracting men's notice, not needing repetition. Cornill, however, following Luther, gives \"evil after evil,\" changing one letter m the Hebrew for \"one,\" so as to get the word \"after.\" For ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "is come",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " read, with the Revised Version, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "it cometh.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It is the nearness, not the actual arrival, of the end, that is in the prophet's thoughts. He writes in  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 595-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Jerusalem was not taken till ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "s.c.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "588 Ezekiel 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The execution of the judgment announced in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:2-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", arranged in four strophes: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:5-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:10-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:15-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:23-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - The first strophe depicts the end as a terrible calamity, and as near at hand. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are repeated as a refrain in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with slight modifications. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Thus saith the Lord Jehovah: Misfortune, a singular misfortune, behold, it cometh. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". End cometh: there cometh the end; it waketh upon thee; behold, it cometh. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The fate cometh upon thee, inhabitants of the land: the time cometh, the day is near; tumult and not joy upon the mountains. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Now speedily will I pour out my fury upon thee, and accomplish mine anger on thee; and judge thee according to thy ways, and bring upon thee all thine abominations. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". My eye shall not look with pity upon thee, and I shall not spare; according to thy ways will I bring it upon thee, and thy abominations shall be in the midst of thee, that ye may know that I, Jehovah, am smiting. - Misfortune of a singular kind shall come. רעה is made more emphatic by אחת רעה, in which אחת is placed first for the sake of emphasis, in the sense of unicus, singularis; a calamity singular (unique) of its kind, such as never had occurred before (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 5:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the poetical הקיץ, it (the end) waketh upon thee, is suggested by the paronomasia with הקּץ. The force of the words is weakened by supplying Jehovah as the subject to הקיץ, in opposition to the context. And it will not do to supply רעה (evil) from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as the subject to  הנּה באה (behold, it cometh). באה is construed impersonally: It cometh, namely, every dreadful thing which the end brings with it. The meaning of tzephirâh is doubtful. The only other passage in which it occurs is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 28:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it is used in the sense of diadem or crown, which is altogether unsuitable here. Raschi has therefore had recourse to the Syriac and Chaldee צפרא, aurora, tempus matutinum, and Hvernick has explained it accordingly, \"the dawn of an evil day.\" But the dawn is never used as a symbol or omen of misfortune, not even in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but solely as the sign of the bursting forth of light or of salvation. Abarbanel was on the right track when he started from the radical meaning of צפר, to twist, and taking tzephirâh in the sense of orbis, ordo, or periodical return, understood it as probably denoting rerum fatique vicissitudinem in orbem redeuntem (Ges. Thes. p. 1188). But it has been justly observed, that the rendering succession, or periodical return, can only give a forced sense in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 7:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Winer has given a better rendering, viz., fatum, malum fatale, fate or destiny, for which he refers to the Arabic tsabramun, intortum, then fatum haud mutandum inevitabile. Different explanations have also been given of הד הרים. But the opinion that it is synonymous with הידד, the joyous vintage cry (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 16:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is a more probable one than that it is an unusual form of הוד, splendor, gloria. So much at any rate is obvious from the context, that the hapax legomenon dh̀ is the antithesis of מהוּמה, tumult, or the noise of war. The shouting of the mountains, is shouting, a rejoicing upon the mountains. מקּרוב, from the immediate vicinity, in a temporal not a local sense, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ( equals  immediately). For כּלּה , see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 6:1-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ";12. The remainder of the strophe (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
